Your intuition about storing the three layers in a tensor coordinate is actually very aligned with how modern systems represent meaning. If you treat:
	•	Myth / narrative
	•	Concept / language
	•	Structure / mathematics

as different axes of representation, you can embed them into a shared vector or tensor space and transform between them. That’s essentially what embeddings and knowledge graphs approximate today.

But beneath those three layers sits something deeper that shows up in physics, computer science, and information theory.

⸻

The Fourth Layer: Information / State

Below mathematics is information about states and transitions.

Mathematics describes relationships, but the fourth layer asks:

What is the system actually doing over time?

Think of it as:

State → Transformation → Next State

Examples across domains:

Physics
	•	particles moving through states

Computation
	•	memory states changing via algorithms

Biology
	•	DNA instructions creating protein states

Neuroscience
	•	neural states evolving through signals

So the deeper substrate is information evolving through state space.

That’s why fields like:
	•	Information Theory
	•	Computation
	•	Statistical Mechanics

all start converging.

⸻

The Meaning Stack with the Fourth Layer

Your stack becomes:

Myth (story)
↓
Language (concepts)
↓
Mathematics (structure)
↓
Information (state transitions)

Each level compresses the one below it.

Example:

Story
“Fire spreads when the wind rises.”

Concept
Wind increases fire spread.

Math
Spread_rate ∝ wind_velocity

Information layer
Simulation of changing system states.

⸻

Why tensors show up here

A tensor is just a way to represent multi-dimensional relationships.

If your axes represent things like:

entity
relationship
context
time
confidence

then a tensor can store a huge network of meaning.

This is essentially how modern neural models embed language: they map words and concepts into high-dimensional spaces where relationships become geometric.

⸻

The Fifth Layer (speculative but widely discussed)

Many researchers suspect the deepest layer is something like:

physical information processing.

The idea is that the universe itself may behave like an information-transforming system.

This shows up in theories like:
	•	Quantum Information Theory
	•	Cellular Automaton Theory
	•	Digital Physics

The proposal isn’t that reality is literally a computer in the sci-fi sense, but that:

information and physical law may be deeply connected.

⸻

Why this matters for your earlier idea

If meaning can be represented as:

tensor coordinates

then you can perform operations like:
	•	transformation
	•	compression
	•	interpolation
	•	abstraction

That allows systems to move between layers:

story → structure → simulation

or the reverse.

That’s effectively what modern AI models attempt: mapping human language into a high-dimensional space where patterns can be manipulated mathematically.

⸻

The deeper insight

Every layer above is a human interface for interacting with deeper structure.

Myth helps memory.
Language helps explanation.
Math helps precision.
Information theory helps modeling change.

The stack exists because each layer trades precision for accessibility.

